Employees;



Employees are trained to detect a spill / release and initiate an emergency response sequence by notifying the appropriate plant personnel.



Emergency Recognition and Prevention;



Adequately trained personnel are assigned to the ammonia refrigeration engine rooms to ensure the ammonia refrigeration system is operated properly and protection guidelines are met.  A preventive maintenance check for inspection has been developed.  Piping and Instrument Drawings (P&ID's) of the system including safety devices such as relief valve locations are mapped out in the facilities command center.  



Safe Distance and Safe Places of Refuge;



Safe distances will be determined by using the DOT Emergency Response Guidebook.  Prevailing winds are determined by wind-socks located at the top of designated silos.  Places of refuge are determined at the time of the incident based on traffic, time of day, Plant involved, wind direction and other dangers.  



Site Security and Control;



Upon arrival at the site of the release, the incident commander will assure that all individuals needing first aid are attended to, and steps are taken to control the general public from exposure to the release.  ID Cards are used to identify trained personnel (Yellow in color).  Police, Fire Fighters and security guards are given instruction on badge identification.  Security guards will be assigned to strategic points in the cold zone to prevent unauthorized entry or re-entry into the warm or hot zones.  



Evacuation Routes and Procedures;



Floor plans are posted in each Plant and show emergency escape routes for fire, chemical leak or spill.  Chemical leaks or spill evacuations are based on wind direction.  Supervisors are trained on how to evacuate employees and on where to assemble for proper accountability.  Employee trai

ning is accomplished by performing drills. 









Decontamination;



Responders contaminated employees and equipment will be decontaminated in the warm zone by company trained personnel or Tulare Fire Department personnel.  A brush with soap and water is used to clean workers and the equipment.  Containment pools for collecting contaminated rinse water are used.  Waste water is processed before disposal. 



Emergency Medical Treatment;



All employees trained in 24 hour Emergency Response are trained in CPR and First Aid as well.  Fire department personnel will assist in first aid measures as necessary.  



Emergency Alerting and Response Provisions;



Points of contact and phone numbers for emergencies, fire or chemical release of a hazardous chemical are posted on bulletin boards at various locations in each plant.  A list is kept in our emergency response command center and in the incident commander organizer binder. Fire alarms and two-way radios as well as word of mouth are used to communicate the message that there has been a spill or leak. An anhydrous ammonia detection and alarm system is installed in each engine-room and will alarm in the event of an anhydrous ammonia leak/spill.



Critique After an Incident;



As soon as possible after each incident a critique of the events that occurred is conducted to retain correct information. The critique is used to make necessary changes to the facilities plan, so that improvements can be implemented for any future incidents.  



Training



To have individuals participate with the stopping of a release, training to the Hazardous Materials Technician Level is required on all shifts.  Employees will receive an initial 24-hour training and will attend an annual 8-hour refresher training to keep their certification current.



